"Höreth-Böntgen D., Böhle W.","""Exotic animal diseases"" - What we should be prepared for [""Exotische tierseuchen"" - Worauf sollten wir uns vorbereiten?]",2010,"Praktische Tierarzt","91","6",,"506","512",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77953997498&partnerID=40&md5=427b9d25477891bb84c6ab68d8f9246a","Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut, Bundesforschungsinstitut für Tiergesundheit, Institut für Epidemiologie, Seestraße 55, 16868 Wusterhausen, Germany; Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut, Bundesforschungsinstitut für Tiergesundheit, AG-Internationale Tiergesundheit, Südufer 10, 17493 Greifswald, Insel Riems, Germany","Höreth-Böntgen, D., Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut, Bundesforschungsinstitut für Tiergesundheit, Institut für Epidemiologie, Seestraße 55, 16868 Wusterhausen, Germany; Böhle, W., Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut, Bundesforschungsinstitut für Tiergesundheit, AG-Internationale Tiergesundheit, Südufer 10, 17493 Greifswald, Insel Riems, Germany","With the appearance of bluetongue and its expansive establishment in Germany in 2007 and 2008, the term ""exotic disease"" becomes questionable and its validity has to be reviewed. It might be more advisable to use terms like ""emerging-or re-emerging diseases"" instead. Foot-and Mouth Disease, lastly seen in Germany in 1988, i. e. more than 20 years ago, could serve as a good example and would appear for many to be an exotic disease should it re-emerge in Germany. Many so-called ""exotic animal epidemics"", originating in the tropics and subtropics, have been on the move into supposedly cooler regions for years. Therefore, relations between ""global warming"" and improved habitat conditions have to be considered at least for vector-borne diseases. This paper reflects on a number of diseases of immediate concern present in European neighbour countries or in the mediterranean neighbourhood. Some of these diseases, classified as potentially relevant in respect to an incursion, are presented in more detail.","Climate change; Epizootic; Vector-borne diseases; Zoonosis","Animalia",,,,,,"Balança, G., Gaidet, N., Savini, G., Vollot, B., Foucart, A., Reiter, P., Boutonnier, A., Moniçat, F., Low west nile virus circulation in wild birds in an area of recurring outbreaks in Southern France (2009) Vector-borne and Zoonotic Dis., 9 (6), pp. 737-741; Barzon, L., Squarzon, L., Cattari, M., Franchin, E., Pagni, S., Cusinato, R., Palù, G., West nile virus infection in Veneto Region, Italy 2008-2009 (2009) Eurosurveillance, 14 (31), pp. 1-4; Dufour, B., Moutou, F., Hattenberger, A.M., Rodhain, F., Global change: Impact, management, risk approach and health measures - The case of Europe (2008) Rev sei tech (Off Int Epiz), 27 (2), pp. 541-550; (2009) Development of Aedes Albopictus Risk Maps, , ECDC, ECDC Technical Report, Stockholm, May 2009; Peste des Petits Ruminants (PPR): An increasing threat to small ruminant production in Africa and Asia (2009) EMPRES Transboundary Animal Diseases Bulletin, 32, pp. 2-8. , FAO; Hubalek, Z., Halouzka, J., West nile fever - A reemerging mosquito-borne viral disease in Europe (1999) Emerg. Infect. Dis., 5 (5), pp. 643-650; Karaoglu, T., Özgünlük, I., Demír, B., Özkul, A., Burg, I., Seroprevalence of culicoides-borne disease in cattle in European Turkey (2007) Ankara Univ Vet Fak Derg, 54, pp. 121-125; A new professional initiative - One health initiative task force: Final report (2008) J. Am. Vet Med. Assoc., , One Health, July 15; Pascucci, J., Conte, A., Scacchia, M., Use of geographic information systems to identify areas at risk of introducing Amblyomma variegatum and A. hebraeum to Italy (2007) Vet Ital, 43 (3), pp. 655-661; Pluskota, B., Storch, V., Braunbeck, T., Beck, M., Becker, N., First Record of Aedes {Stegomya albopictus) Skuse, (Diptera: Culicidae) in Germany (2008) Eur. Mosq Bull., 26, pp. 1-5; (2009) Ephemeral Fever, Bovine - Israel: Southwest, Susp., , www.isid.org, ProMed-mail, Archive Number: 20090713.2502, 13. July 2009, Promed, Internatio